1 Exercise 2

Explain what Box-Cox transformation is and when it is applicable.

A Box Cox transformation is a transformation of non-normal dependent variables into a normal shape. Normality is an important assumption for many statistical techniques; if your data is not normal, applying a Box-Cox means that you are able to run a broader number of tests [1].

3.1 Transformations and Adjustments
There are two transformations, logarithms and power, which depend on the parameter \(\lambda\) and is defined as follows: \[ w_t = \begin{cases} log(y_t) & \text{if $\lambda$ = 0;} \\ (sign(y_t)|y_t|^{\lambda}-1)/\lambda & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases} \]

This is a modified Box-Cox transformation, allowing for the negative values of \(y_t > 0\).

The logarithm is a Box_cox transformation is always a natural logarithm. If \(\lambda\) = 0, natural logarithms are used. Otherwise, \(\lambda \not= 0\), a power transformation is used follows by some single scaling.

If \(\lambda\) = 1, then \(w_t = y_t -1\), so the transformed data is shifted downwards but there is no change in the shape of the time series. For all other values of \(\lambda\), the time series will change shape.

A good value of \(\lambda\) is one which makes the size of the seasonal variation about the same across the whole series, as that makes the forecasting model simpler.

9.7 ARIMA modelling in fable
When fitting an AMIRA model to a set of (non-seasonal) time series data, it may need to be transformed to stabilize the variance, also know as heteroscedasticity. This transformation is used to make the series stationary, which is an assumption of the AMIMA model.

[1] https://www.statisticshowto.com/probability-and-statistics/normal-distributions/box-cox-transformation/

For the following series, find the appropriate Box-Cox transformation and order of differencing in order to obtain stationary data.

Turkish GDP appears to have trend but no seasonality.

Logarithmic transformations can be utilized to stabilize the variance of a time series, while differencing can stabilize the mean of a time series by eliminating or reducing trend and seasonality, and removing changes in the level of a time series.

The ACF plot can identify non-stationary time series, as the ACF of stationary data will decrease to zero rapidly, while that of non-stationary data will decline slowly. Additionally, a frequently observed characteristic of non-stationary data is a large, positive value of the first lag, \(r_1\). In the first ACF plot, the data slowly approaches zero over time while the difference in GDP hovers around zero. This is one indicator that differencing will need to occur.

## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   lb_stat lb_pvalue
##     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1    9.88     0.451

The ACF plot of the differenced Turkish GDP displays a striking resemblance to that of a white noise series, with only a single autocorrelation outside the 95% limits, and the Ljung-Box Q* statistic yielding a p-value of 0.451 (at \(h\) = 10). These findings indicate that the yearly fluctuation in GDP is essentially a random occurrence, unrelated to those of previous years.

2.2 Global_economy Lambda

First, find the appropriate lambda for the time series.

The guerro feature calculates the optimal value of \(\lambda\) for Box-Cox transformation by employing the Guerrero method, with a resulting value of 0.16 identified as best choice for this time series.

2.3 Global_economy Differencing

To determining whether differencing is necessary, utilize a unit root test. This is a statistical hypothesis test specifically designed to assess stationarity and evaluate the need for differencing.

## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
##       <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1      1.50        0.01

The objective of conducting the unit root test is to examine the null hypothesis that the data are stationary, and detect any indications that contradict this assumption. If the resulting p-value < 0.05, it implies that differencing is necessary. In the case of the Turkish GDP, the p-value is 0.01, which leads to the rejection of the null hypothesis.

## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
##       <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1    0.0889         0.1

Once we difference the data, the test statistic becomes much smaller, and the range we would expect for stationary data is met by a p-value > 0.05.

To double check that only one difference was needed, we run the following:

## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   ndiffs
##    <int>
## 1      1
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   nsdiffs
##     <int>
## 1       0

The process above involves using a sequence of KPSS tests to identify the suitable number of first differences required, which is one. Once lambda is incorporated, no further differencing is needed.

Typically, determining suitable values for \(p\) and \(q\) based only on a time plot is not feasible. Nonetheless, in some instances, one can leverage the ACF and PACF plots, which are closely connected, to identify appropriate values for \(p\) and \(q\). \(p\) is the order of the autoregressive part while \(q\) is the order of the moving average part. After transforming and differencing the time series, both of these plots have lags that remain within the confidence intervals, meaning that those lags are not autocorrelated.

5.2 Question 1

Use ARIMA() to find an appropriate ARIMA model. What model was selected? Check that the residuals look like white noise. Plot forecasts for the next 10 periods.

## Series: Passengers 
## Model: ARIMA(0,2,1) 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1
##       -0.8756
## s.e.   0.0722
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 4.671:  log likelihood=-87.8
## AIC=179.61   AICc=179.93   BIC=182.99

\[y_t = -0.88{\epsilon}_{t-1} + {\epsilon}_t \]

The function ARIMA() automatically chooses the best model. There are two degrees of first differencing involved, and one order of the moving average part, while there is no order of the autoregressive portion. The \(\epsilon_t\) is white noise with a standard deviation of 2.16. This specific model, AMIMA(0, 2, 1) only has only parameter, \(ma1\) which is the moving average term of order 1. Since it is without a constant, this is a linear exponential smoothing model. This is estimated to be -0.8756. The log likelihood tells you how well the model fits to the data. In terms of the AIC and BIC, the lowest values are preferred. Therefore, since this model was automatically chosen, we would assume these two values are the lowest compared to other models.

From around 1989 and forward, the time plot shows a slight increase in the variability from the time prior. In addition, the ACF plot demonstrates that the residuals look like white noise as there as no lags above the confidence intervals. The histogram seems to be distributed in a normal manner.

After 2011, the projected trend is positive. The prediction intervals shown are 80% and 95%, which indicates that Australia can expect their passenger numbers to fall within one of those segments with that amount of uncertainty in the forecast.

5.3 Question 2

Write this model in terms of the backshift operator.

\[ARIMA(0, 2, 1) = (1-B)^dy_t = (1 - 0.88B){\epsilon}_t \]

In this model, \(d = 2\). In addition, there will be no constant, \(c\), since \(d\) is greater than two. Backtracking to Question 1, since \(c\) = 0 and \(d\) = 2, we can expect long-term forecasts will follow a straight line. In the 10-year forecast, this seems to be the case in a ‘shorter-term’ scenario.

5.4 Question 3

Plot forecasts from an ARIMA(0,1,0) model with drift and compare these to part 1.

This model will be a random walk with drift without a constant.

## Series: Passengers 
## Model: ARIMA(0,1,0) w/ drift 
## 
## Coefficients:
##       constant
##         1.3669
## s.e.    0.3319
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 4.629:  log likelihood=-89.08
## AIC=182.17   AICc=182.48   BIC=185.59

As seen in a prior naïve method, one way to modify the forecasts is to allow them to fluctuate upwards or downwards over time. This adjustment, referred to as the drift, is determined by the average change observed in the past data. This is equivalent to drawing a line between the first and last observation, and extrapolating it into the future. As presented in Question 1, the trend is positive. A similar forecast is seen in the method but appears to be more gradual. The prediction intervals are tighter and higher than they were previously. The AIC and BIC are slightly lower too.

The residuals almost mirror the ARIMA(0, 2, 1) model. The ACF plot remains to demonstrate that the residuals look like white noise as there as no lags above the confidence intervals. The histogram seems to be distributed in a normal manner with less outliers.
